---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section id="work-shift" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <h2
        class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
      >
        Your work no longer does
      </h2>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 grid items-center gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="lg:order-last">
        <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
          <p>
            In the framework era you were the frontend expert: deep in one
            repo, choosing the router and the component library, caring less
            about the backend because that was someone else's floor. With
            agents taking the lower-level implementation,
            <mark>you level up a floor</mark>. You go from single-repo
            specialist to system-level generalist: you care about the whole
            stack, and you cross the frontend and backend boundaries that were
            never really meant to be walls.
          </p>
          <p>
            Here is what that feels like. You spot a bug. You do not know that
            code line by line, but you understand it at the system level: what
            it touches, why it fails, roughly where the fix lives. Before, you
            would have handed it to the person who owns that code. Now you fire
            up an agent, steer it toward the fix, follow its reasoning, and the
            change lands.
          </p>
          <p class="font-medium text-neutral-100">
            Your scope is now the frontend, the backend, the design system.
            Each agent still wakes up inside a single box.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <VizPlaceholder
          label="MultiRepoCubes island: frontend, backend, design system cubes, one agent in each, no connections"
          ratio="aspect-[4/3]"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
